Categorizing Cats and Dogs¶

If the MNIST dataset is the "hello world" of Neural Nets, writing a CNN that can tell the difference between cats and dogs is "build a calculator."

Building a Cat/Dog-classifier is a right of passage and a great example of a binary classifier in neural nets.

Set the device¶

In the above menu, go to Runtime and then Change Runtime Type, choose T4 GPU. This will give us access to GPU training (at least temporarily, there seems to be a limited amount of credit per account).

After doing this, we'll need to set our model and our datasets to the "cuda" mode. An easy way to do this is to assign this to variable.

import torch

device = "cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu"

Copied!

Load the Dataset¶

We're going to load our dataset which is some folders of cats and dogs. We'll use PIL.Image to wrap these and Ipython.display.display (think of this as "fancy print) to display some random ones.

from PIL import Image
import glob
from google.colab import drive
from IPython.display import display
import random

# Normal old mount the gdrive
drive.mount('/content/gdrive')

# Specify where the data is (maybe take a look at it)
train_folder = "/content/gdrive/MyDrive/datasets/cats_and_dogs/training_set"
test_folder = "/content/gdrive/MyDrive/datasets/cats_and_dogs/test_set"

# Print out a few random cats from our train set. These don't matter for training, but will be helpful for explaining some ideas.
random_cat = Image.open(random.choice(glob.glob(f"{train_folder}/cats/*.jpg")))
random_dog = Image.open(random.choice(glob.glob(f"{train_folder}/dogs/*.jpg")))

# Fancy print our random cat and dog
display(random_cat)
display(random_dog)

Setting up the Preprocessor¶

The preprocessor is a series of transformations we apply to our dataset to make it:

  • Uniform
  • Add some variation

In our case, we're going to just make our images all uniform (the same size) but there are other kinds of transformers that do things like flip images and crop them to add more varity to our training examples without actually adding more photos.

The first thing we'll want to do is resize.

from torchvision import transforms

resize = transforms.Resize(size=(128, 128))

We can see what this does to our test images.

display(resize(random_cat))
display(resize(random_dog))

It squashes our images down.

Next, well need to turn it into a tensor. Let's combine resizing and turning into a tensor into a two-step preprocessor.

preprocessor = transforms.Compose([
    resize,
    transforms.ToTensor()
])

And then inspect what this will do to our test images.

display(transform(random_cat))
print(f"Shape is {transform(random_cat).shape}")

display(transform(random_dog))
print(f"Shape is {transform(random_dog).shape}")

Load our Datasets¶

Next we'll want to load these as dataset objects. Remember, pytorch has two concepts here, one is a dataset which is a wrapper around the training and test examples. The other is the dataloader which is a wrapper around the batches of examples. We'll initialize both.

While doing this, pick a batch_size. Something between 10 and 100.

from torchvision import datasets
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader

batch_size = ...

train_data = datasets.ImageFolder(
    root=train_folder,
    transform=preprocessor,
    target_transform=None,
)
test_data = datasets.ImageFolder(
    root=test_folder,
    transform=preprocessor
)
train_dataloader = DataLoader(
    dataset=train_data,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    shuffle=True
)
test_dataloader = DataLoader(
    dataset=test_data,
    batch_size=batch_size
)

print(f"Train data:\n{train_data}\nTest data:\n{test_data}")
print(f"Train dataloader:\n{train_dataloader}\nTest dataloader:\n{test_dataloader}")

Design our Neural Network¶

Now we're going to design our Convolutional Neural Network. This is a much more

import torch
from torch import nn

class ImageClassifier(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        
        # The first Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 3, 128, 128]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64]
        self.conv_layer_1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 3, padding=1)
        self.relu_1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.maxpool_1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The second Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 32, 32]
        self.conv_layer_2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 512, 3, padding=1)
        self.relu_2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)
        
        # The third Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 16, 16]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 8, 8]
        self.conv_layer_3 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.relu_3 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The fourth Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 32, 32]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 16, 16]
        self.conv_layer_4 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.relu_4 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_4 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The fifth Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 8, 8]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 4, 4]
        self.conv_layer_5 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.relu_5 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_5 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_5 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The sixth Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 4, 4]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 2, 2]
        self.conv_layer_6 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1)
        self.relu_6 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_6 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_6 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The Classifier
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 2, 2]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 2]
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
          nn.Flatten(),
          nn.Linear(in_features=512*2*2, out_features=2),
        )

    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor):
        x = self.conv_layer_1(x)
        x = self.relu_1(x)
        x = self.bn_1(x)
        x = self.maxpool_1(x)
        x = self.conv_layer_2(x)
        x = self.relu_2(x)
        x = self.bn_2(x)
        x = self.maxpool_2(x)
        x = self.conv_layer_3(x)
        x = self.relu_3(x)
        x = self.bn_3(x)
        x = self.maxpool_3(x)
        x = self.conv_layer_4(x)
        x = self.relu_4(x)
        x = self.bn_4(x)
        x = self.maxpool_4(x)
        x = self.conv_layer_5(x)
        x = self.relu_5(x)
        x = self.bn_5(x)
        x = self.maxpool_5(x)
        x = self.conv_layer_6(x)
        x = self.relu_6(x)
        x = self.bn_6(x)
        x = self.maxpool_6(x)
        x = self.classifier(x)
        return x

After this, initialize our model.

# Initialize the model
model = ImageClassifier().to(device)

# Inspect it
print(model)

Initialize your Loss Fn and Optimizer¶

You'll need a loss function and optimizer.

# Instantiate an optimizer (Stochastic Gradient Decent)
optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01)

# Instantiate a Loss Function
loss_fn = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

Training¶

Now we're going to do our training loop, pick a number of epochs and go to town.

Note: This is going to be a lot slower than our previous models. Start with epoch=1, you can alwauy go back and run this cell again so long as you initialized your model in the previous one.

model.train()
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}")
    
    total_train_loss = 0
    total_accurate = 0
    for i, (X, y) in enumerate(train_dataloader):
        X = X.to(device)
        y = y.to(device)

        print(X.shape)
        print(y.shape)
        
        # 1. Forward Pass
        y_pred = model(X)

        # 2. Calculate Loss
        loss = loss_fn(y_pred, y)
        loss.backward()
        
        # 3. Decend        
        optimizer.step()
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        # Add up our success
        total_train_loss += loss.item()
        total_accurate += (y_pred.argmax(dim=1) == y).sum().item()

        if i > 10:
            break

        if i % 100 == 0:
            print(f"Batch {i}/{len(train_dataloader)}, loss was {loss.item()}")
    
    print(f"Accuracy: {total_accurate/len(train_data)}")

import torch
from torch import nn

class ImageClassifier(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()

        # The first Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 3, 128, 128]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64]
        self.conv_layer_1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 3, padding=1)
        self.relu_1 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64)
        self.maxpool_1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The second Convolutional Layer
        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 32, 32]
        self.conv_layer_2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 512, 3, padding=1)
        self.relu_2 = nn.ReLU()
        self.bn_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512)
        self.maxpool_2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # The third Convolutional Layer

        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 8, 8]

        self.relu_5 = nn.ReLU()

        self.maxpool_5 = nn.MaxPool2d(2)

        # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 4, 4]
        # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 2, 2]
        self.conv_layer_6 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1)

          nn.Flatten(),
          nn.Linear(in_features=512*2*2, out_features=2),
        )

    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor):
        print("Layer 1")

        print(x.shape)

        print(x.shape)

model = ImageClassifier()

# Instantiate an optimizer (Stochastic Gradient Decent)

import torch from torch import nn class ImageClassifier(nn.Module): def __init__(self): super().__init__() # The first Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 3, 128, 128] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64] self.conv_layer_1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 3, padding=1) self.relu_1 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_1 = nn.BatchNorm2d(64) self.maxpool_1 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The second Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 64, 64] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 32, 32] self.conv_layer_2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 512, 3, padding=1) self.relu_2 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_2 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512) self.maxpool_2 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The third Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 16, 16] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 8, 8] self.conv_layer_3 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1) self.relu_3 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_3 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512) self.maxpool_3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The fourth Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 64, 32, 32] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 16, 16] self.conv_layer_4 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1) self.relu_4 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_4 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512) self.maxpool_4 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The fifth Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 8, 8] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 4, 4] self.conv_layer_5 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1) self.relu_5 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_5 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512) self.maxpool_5 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The sixth Convolutional Layer # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 4, 4] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 2, 2] self.conv_layer_6 = nn.Conv2d(512, 512, kernel_size=3, padding=1) self.relu_6 = nn.ReLU() self.bn_6 = nn.BatchNorm2d(512) self.maxpool_6 = nn.MaxPool2d(2) # The Classifier # Input Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 512, 2, 2] # Output Shape: [BATCH_SIZE, 2] self.classifier = nn.Sequential( nn.Flatten(), nn.Linear(in_features=512*2*2, out_features=2), ) def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor): print("Layer 1") print(x.shape) x = self.conv_layer_1(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_1(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_1(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_1(x) print(x.shape) print("Layer 2") x = self.conv_layer_2(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_2(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_2(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_2(x) print(x.shape) print("Layer 3") x = self.conv_layer_3(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_3(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_3(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_3(x) print(x.shape) print("Layer 4") x = self.conv_layer_4(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_4(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_4(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_4(x) print(x.shape) print("Layer 5") x = self.conv_layer_5(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_5(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_5(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_5(x) print(x.shape) print("Layer 6") x = self.conv_layer_6(x) print(x.shape) x = self.relu_6(x) print(x.shape) x = self.bn_6(x) print(x.shape) x = self.maxpool_6(x) print(x.shape) print("Classifier") x = self.classifier(x) print(x.shape) return x model = ImageClassifier() # Instantiate an optimizer (Stochastic Gradient Decent) optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.01) # Instantiate a Loss Function loss_fn = nn.CrossEntropyLoss() print(model)

num_epochs = 1

model.train()
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}")

    total_train_loss = 0
    total_accurate = 0
    for i, (X, y) in enumerate(train_dataloader):

        if i > 1:
            break

        X = X.to(device)
        y = y.to(device)

        print(X.shape)
        print(y.shape)

        # 1. Forward Pass
        y_pred = model(X)

        # 2. Calculate Loss
        loss = loss_fn(y_pred, y)
        loss.backward()

        # 3. Decend
        optimizer.step()
        optimizer.zero_grad()

        # Add up our success
        total_train_loss += loss.item()
        total_accurate += (y_pred.argmax(dim=1) == y).sum().item()

        if i > 10:
            break

        if i % 100 == 0:
            print(f"Batch {i}/{len(train_dataloader)}, loss was {loss.item()}")

    print(f"Accuracy: {total_accurate/len(train_data)}")
